# **About the freeDSP** {#about-the-freedsp}

The freeDSP is a cost-effective real-time audio signal processing solution for researchers and the do-it-yourself community. It is a bare circuit board that can be incorporated into your own projects. It comes with no housing. Easy assembling and simple programmability are the main focus. It is based on Analog Devices’ ADAU1701 DSP chip in bundle with the free graphical development environment [SigmaStudio](http://www.analog.com/en/design-center/processors-and-dsp/evaluation-and-development-software/ss_sigst_02.html). The programming model is function-block based – comparable to other graphical programming languages like [PureData](https://puredata.info/) or [Max/MSP](https://cycling74.com/products/max/). Many prebuilt blocks (e.g., filters, compressors, effects, or logic) can be placed in the signal path via drag and drop. If the included libraries do not have the functions needed, low-level blocks, such as multipliers and delays, can be wired together to create custom algorithms. For more information please refer to the [Analog Devices website](http://www.analog.com/en/design-center/processors-and-dsp/evaluation-and-development-software/ss_sigst_02.html). 

The freeDSP ALLinONE  board offers two analog inputs, a S/PDIF in- and output, and four amplified class-D amplifier outputs. It can be used in various audio applications, e.g.:

- Room compensation / system equalization  
- Digital crossovers in active loudspeaker concepts   
- Multiband dynamics processing  
- Delay compensation / phase shift  
- Bass enhancement  
- Subwoofer integration  
- Advanced instrument audio effect units  
- Stereo image widening  
- …

The plans for the freeDSP ALLinONE  board are published under a Creative Commons Attribution Share-Alike 4.0 license, which allows the unrestricted use and modification of the module.  This means that experienced user may modify his own version of the board, extending it and improving it, as long as they credit freeDSP and release their designs under the same license. The freeDSP brand and freeDSP logo are copyright of Sebastian Merchel and Ludwig Kormann and cannot be used without formal permission. This getting started guide is published under the same CC license.

# **Revision 2019 \- Information and changes \- I²S-Issue** {#revision-2019---information-and-changes---i²s-issue}

2019 we discovered a essential Problem with the digital audio communication on the SMD-B Board. There were two MultiPurpose-Pins unused (MP4/5), but they’re very important when it comes to getting digital audio on the Board. It turned out that the **freeDSP Standard Connector can’t easily send and receive on same hardware/channel**. The ADAU1701 requires a BCLK-In and a LRCLK-In for all input channel. These Inputs are MP4/5.

**Changes**  
There was nothing changed in terms of general hardware or layout. That means besides this page the board and the Getting Started is still the same. **Please note that the minimal distance to the side is slightly smaller than recommended** in the design guidelines.

There have been added 2 pin header (JP1 & JP2), on which you can change the mode for the Standard Connector. Whether its used for Input or Output Purposes.

**Output Mode:**

1. Connect Pin 2 to Pin 1  
   On both JP1 & JP2

**Input Mode** (DSP is Slave):

1. Connect Pin 2 to Pin 3  
   On both JP1 & JP2

**Input Mode** (DSP is Master):

1. Connect all 3 Pins together on both JP1 & JP2

**MultiPurpose Mode** (if you only use Input or Output Mode on all Connectors or not use  
digital audio at all)

1. Disconnect all Pins.   
   JP1: Pin1 \= MP11 | Pin3 \= MP5  
   JP2: Pin1 \= MP10 | Pin3 \= MP4

# **How to get the freeDSP up and running** {#how-to-get-the-freedsp-up-and-running}

The following steps will guide you through the workflow to get your freeDSP up and running. Everything starts with the decision for the freeDSP ALLinONE  and ordering all necessary components **and** a programmer. After soldering the board, the required software has to be installed. Finally, the program will be transferred to the board and fine-tuned.

## **Get everything needed** {#get-everything-needed}

You will need a soldering iron plus some soldering experience to assemble the surface mounted and through hole components. However, we think it is not feasible for everyone. We cannot offer a completely assembled version of the freeDSP. However, there are [companies](https://www.eurocircuits.com/), which print the pcb, solder the components and deliver the ready to use board. Note that you need either **CY7C68013A mini board** or the standard **USBi** adapter from Analog Devices ([EVAL-ADUSB2EBZ](http://www.analog.com/en/evaluation/eval-adusb2ebz/eb.html)) or the **freeUSBi programmer** (see the freeDSP website) for programming your freeDSP.

1. **Order the freeDSP kit.** Sometimes *centralized buying* of PCB and all parts is offered. Please contact the developer of this board regarding this. Please keep in mind that freeDSP is a spare-time, non-commercial project. It may take some time until a new batch of boards and/or kits is ordered.

(a.)	**Alternatively,** you can manufacture your own circuit board or modify and extend the original design. This might be the faster option, but needs more expertise (and money) to get up and running. 

(a.) **Alternatively,** manufacture the printed circuit board and order all parts yourself.   
You might want to locally organize centralized buying and board production together with some friends. You can find the necessary KiCAD files of the board on the freeDSP website [www.freeDSP.cc](http://www.freedsp.cc). You will also need to order all electronic parts. The components can be ordered via [DigiKey](http://www.digikey.de) (or other distributors). The trickiest part is soldering the DSP, which comes in an SMD packaging. There is a [video showing the soldering process](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8vDUtkF31B0&spfreload=10) (for the freeDSP Classic; currently only in German language). However, this is definitely not recommended for soldering beginners\! If you are in doubt of your skills better ask a friend to help you.

Every freeDSP user will need a programmer, an external power supply and a Windows PC plus the programming software. 

2. Install **SigmaStudio** (free) on your PC as described below and order or build a **programmer**. We highly recommend using our freeUSBi programmer or the original USBi programmer EVAL-ADUSB2EBZ. This enables interactive modification of your program on the DSP from within SigmaStudio. The original USBi programmer can be bought directly from [Analog Devices](http://www.analog.com/en/evaluation/eval-adusb2ebz/eb.html) for 80 $. You will need to buy the programmer only once. **Alternatively**, you can buy the **CY7C68013A mini board** on [eBay](http://www.ebay.de/sch/i.html?_from=R40&_sacat=0&_nkw=CY7C68013A&LH_PrefLoc=2&_sop=15). CY7C68013A mini board can be plugged on the freeDSP board without any additional cable. It provides the same functionality like the freeUSBi programmer.   
3. Finally, you will need a **power supply** for your board and some **cables** to connect your equipment.

## **Solder the board**  {#solder-the-board}

You can find the part list and the assembly print in the appendix. With a soldering iron with a fine tip plus some soldering experience you should be able to assemble your board. The CS8422 should be soldered first using reflow soldering or hot air. There are many tutorials on how to solder QFN packages like the CS8422, e.g. [this one](https://www.youtube.com/watch?reload=9&v=c_Qt5CtUlqY). 

## **Preparing the CY7C68013A Mini Board**  {#preparing-the-cy7c68013a-mini-board}

You can find the part list and the assembly print in the appendix. With a soldering iron with a fine tip plus some soldering experience you should be able to assemble your board.

To configure the freeDSP you will need a Windows computer running SigmaStudio. It can be downloaded from the [Analog Devices website](http://www.analog.com/en/design-center/processors-and-dsp/evaluation-and-development-software/ss_sigst_02.html) with no charge. However, you will have to create an account.

## **Create a schematic** {#create-a-schematic}

To create the signal processing schematic, which is supposed to run on the DSP, change from the ‘Hardware Configuration’ tab to the ‘Schematic’ tab. The menu on the left will now show all available processing blocks, structured into various categories. First, drag and drop the audio input block and two audio output blocks into the schematic. The inputs can be found via ‘IO/Input/Input’ and outputs via ‘IO/Output/Output’. 

To get started, we want to implement a simple 2-way crossover filter. Therefore, drag the corresponding block into your schematic: ’Filters/Crossover/Single Precision/2-Way/Crossover’. Configure the modules as shown in Figure 7\.   
![Macintosh HD:Users:Basti:Dropbox:UNI:freeDSP WEBSITE:Manual:Vorlagen:Bilder SA Ludwig:Studienarbeit\_Ludwig\_Kormann\_Seite\_62\_Bild\_0001.png][image8]  
**Figure 7 \- Simple 2-way crossover filter with one audio input and two outputs**

By clicking the blue crossover symbol, the settings menu for the filter appears as shown in Figure 8\. If you are using the USBi programmer, you can change all parameters like filter types or corner frequencies in real-time. This way, you can hear the resulting modifications immediately.   
You can also find a basic schematic in the git-repository of the freeDSP ALLinONE . It provides both inputs (selectable) and connects them to the 4 channels of the amplifiers.  
![Macintosh HD:Users:Basti:Dropbox:UNI:freeDSP WEBSITE:Manual:Vorlagen:Bilder SA Ludwig:Studienarbeit\_Ludwig\_Kormann\_Seite\_63\_Bild\_0001.png][image9]  
**Figure 8 \- Settings window for a 2-way crossover filter**

## **Setting-up operation**  {#setting-up-operation}

The final program needs to be compiled and transferred to the DSP. Therefore, a suitable programmer is needed. To offer real-time programmability the USBi adapter from Analog Devices ([EVAL-ADUSB2EBZ](http://www.analog.com/en/evaluation/eval-adusb2ebz/eb.html)) is recommended, which is currently sold for approximately 80 $. This is the most comfortable way of working with the freeDSP. If the application is intended to run the board only in self-boot mode, a cheaper programmer (e.g., an Arduino) can be used.

### **Transfer your program using the freeUSBi or USBi programmer**  {#transfer-your-program-using-the-freeusbi-or-usbi-programmer}

Connect the freeUSBi programmer or USBi programmer to your freeDSP. Now, connect the adapter to a free USB port on your computer. Then, click ‘Link Compile Download’ as illustrated in Figure 9\. 

![Macintosh HD:Users:Basti:Dropbox:UNI:freeDSP WEBSITE:Manual:Vorlagen:Bilder SA Ludwig:Studienarbeit\_Ludwig\_Kormann\_Seite\_59\_Bild\_0001.png][image10]  
**Figure 9 \- The 'Link Compile Download' button in SigmaStudio loads the schematic into the freeDSP**

That’s it. Your freeDSP is now powered over USB and ready to be wired up with your audio equipment. For operation with a different power supply, see the section [Operate without computer connection](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1K3joEg4iIRMazfqGLaVoBdybitr4o_KIVZfQ-qeNDzs/edit#heading=h.qsh70q) below. 

### **Transfer your program using an Arduino programmer** {#transfer-your-program-using-an-arduino-programmer}

Alternatively, the program can be written to the onboard EEPROM and booted in standalone mode. This offline programming can be done using a microcontroller, e.g. an Arduino Nano or Micro.   
See [Pinout of the Arduino connector](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1K3joEg4iIRMazfqGLaVoBdybitr4o_KIVZfQ-qeNDzs/edit#heading=h.vx1227) on how to connect the Arduino.

The following description will guide you through the necessary steps to setup the software:

1. Download and install the [Arduino software](http://arduino.cc/en/Main/Software) including the Arduino drivers.  
2. Connect your Arduino. After Windows has automatically updated and installed the drivers, you will find your Arduino here: Start/Control Panel/System/ Hardware/Device Manager/Ports (COM & LPT). Please note the number of the COM port. (If Windows does not install the drivers automatically, please have a look in the “Install the drivers” section of the [Arduino guide](http://www.arduino.cc/en/guide/windows). If you own an Arduino with a CH340 chip, you might need to install the [CH340 drivers](http://www.freedsp.cc/downloads/CH340G_USB2SERIAL_Arduino_drivers.zip) manually. If you are running Windows 8.1 the CH340 driver might install automatically.) The following steps require that bootloader is installed on your Arduino, which is the default case when you buy a new board.  
3. Download and unzip the [I2C libraries](http://www.freedsp.cc/downloads/freeDSP_I2C_libraries.zip). Copy the folder ‘freeDSP\_I2C\_libraries’ to the Arduino library: C:\\Program Files (x86)\\Arduino\\libraries  
4. Open the Arduino software and select your Arduino version (Tools/Board/…) and COM port (Tools/Serial Port/…).  
5. Download and unzip this [Arduino sketch](http://www.freedsp.cc/downloads/freeDSP_Arduino_sketch.zip). Open ‘freeDSP.ino’ and upload it. Close the Arduino software.  
6. Download and install [Tera Term](http://ttssh2.sourceforge.jp/index.html.en). 

The previous steps need to be completed only once. In the following, you will now need to locate the program text file generated by SigmaStudio and burn it to the EEPROM.

1. Be sure that the EEPROM programming jumper is in the ‘write enabled’ position as labeled in bottom right corner of Figure 2\.  
2. Please check if your Arduino is still connected to the same USB port as during installation. If not, please identify the active COM port following step 2\.  
3. Open Tera Term, select ‘serial’ in the pop-up window and choose the active COM port connected with your Arduino as shown in Figure 10\. (The default baud rate in Tera Term is 9600, which is also the default baud rate in the latest Arduino sketch. If you are an advanced user, you can manually change the baud rate in the Arduino sketch and Tera Term. We have successfully tested 19200.)  
4. You should get a welcome message from your Arduino ‘… eeprom found … waiting for E2Prom.Hex file…’   
5. Open your SigmaStudio project file (.dspprog) from your project folder and click ‘Link Compile Download’ as illustrated in Figure 9\. Ignore the possible ‘Communication Failure’ message.  
6. Change to the ‘Hardware Configuration’ tab. Right click on the ADAU1701 block and select ‘Write Latest Compilation to E2PROM’ as shown in Figure 11\.   
7. Now switch back to Tera Term and click ‘send file’. Navigate to the subfolder IC2 in your project folder. You will find a file called E2Prom.hex. Select it and confirm. A loading bar will show you the progress of the file transfer.  
8. You are done. If you only see zeros in the terminal, please check if the programming jumper was in the ‘write enabled’ position.

![Mac OS:Users:Basti:Dropbox:UNI:freeDSP WEB + DOKU:GETTING STARTED:Vorlagen:Arduino:Bilder\_Ardiono\_TeraTerm\_Step\_By\_Step:TeraTerm\_choose\_comport.JPG][image11]  
**Figure 10 – Choose COM port in Tera Term**

### **Transfer your program using an EEPROM programmer** {#transfer-your-program-using-an-eeprom-programmer}

As a third option, a dedicated I2C EEPROM programmer can be used, which supports the EEPROM mounted on the board. However, this option is not recommended.

### **Connect your audio equipment and adjust your program**  {#connect-your-audio-equipment-and-adjust-your-program}

After transferring your program, connect your audio equipment to the analog or digital inputs and, depending on your setup, to the analog outputs (pins) or the screw terminals of the amplifiers. Be sure that your **audio equipment is powered off** when making these connections. Please avoid twisting the RCA connectors – just **push and pull** the plugs. Now switch on your connected audio equipment with the volume down low (both source and amplifier). Check if your program (e.g., the crossover) is working as intended, while gradually increasing the volume.  
It is highly recommended to use a measurement microphone to tune your program. Various mics exist on the market, e.g. miniDSPs [UMIK-1](https://www.minidsp.com/products/acoustic-measurement/umik-1). You will also need measurement software like the [Room EQ Wizard](http://www.roomeqwizard.com) (free, Windows), [ARTA](http://www.artalabs.hr) (Windows) or [FuzzMeasure](http://supermegaultragroovy.com/products/FuzzMeasure/) (Mac) or any other software of your choice. 

For our digital crossover example above, you would measure each driver individually and in combination. Using these measurements, you can adjust crossover frequency and slopes or add additional equalizers for each driver. **Please save your modifications in SigmaStudio on a regular basis\! Note that it is NOT possible to transfer a configuration stored on the freeDSP hardware back to your computer.**

## **Operate without computer connection** {#operate-without-computer-connection}

If you are happy with your adjustments, you can continue to operate the freeDSP without a computer. Therefore, you need to write your program permanently in the hardware memory and connect an external power source.

### **Store your program permanently in the freeDSP memory**  {#store-your-program-permanently-in-the-freedsp-memory}

To run the freeDSP without a computer connection, the program needs to be stored in the internal memory of the board – the EEPROM. This step is only necessary for USBi programming, because the program will always be written to the EEPROM if you are using an Arduino. Be sure that the EEPROM programming jumper is in the ‘write enabled’ position as described in Figure 2\. In SigmaStudio change back to the ‘Hardware Configuration’ tab. Right click on the ADAU1701 block and select ‘Write Latest Compilation to E2PROM’ as shown in Figure 11 and confirm the next window. Than right click on the ADAU1701 block again and ‘Check Last Compilation vs. E2PROM’. If you now switch to an external power supply or push the reset button on the freeDSP, the board will load the program from the EEPROM. (If you unplug the USBi programmer from your computer, it also needs to be disconnected from the freeDSP board. Otherwise your freeDSP will not start.)

![Macintosh HD:Users:Basti:Dropbox:UNI:freeDSP WEBSITE:Manual:Vorlagen:Bilder SA Ludwig:Studienarbeit\_Ludwig\_Kormann\_Seite\_60\_Bild\_0001.png][image12]  
**Figure 11 \- Store the latest compiled version of your schematic to the freeDSP**

### **Supply external power**  {#supply-external-power}

If the freeDSP is no longer connected to a computer, it needs an alternate power source. You can use an external supply to power the freeDSP via the screw terminal (recommended). Alternatively you can power the freeDSP via a connected Arduino.

The freeDSP ALLinONE  was tested for input voltages between 4.5V and 24V because of the nominal supply voltage of the amplifier \[TAS5760M, p. 1\]. The maximum input voltage of the switching regulator is specified as 42V. In order to guarantee a voltage lower than this maximum barrier, a Transient Voltage Suppressor Diode \[SMAJ28CA\] with a breakdown voltage between 31.1V and 32.7V is used. Because of the maximum voltage of the amplifiers \[TAS5760\] the board should **never be powered with a voltage above 30V.**  
However, the freeDSP standard connector specifies 12V, so if you plan to use any extensions boards it might be a good idea to opt for 12V. Note, that the extension board adapter does not provide 12V, instead **the 12V pin will just forward the supply voltage.**

You can connect a DC power supply, the USBi programmer and an Arduino at the same time without any problems. We do recommend to supply at least 12V so the two amps get enough peak-peak-voltage. A higher input voltage of up to 24V is even better to get out the most of your board.  
There is no power switch on the freeDSP. It boots automatically once connected to a power supply.

**Troubleshooting**

1. Please take the time to carefully read this getting started guide and have a look at the online application examples. **Please keep in mind that freeDSP is an open-source spare-time project.** Thank you for your understanding\!  
2. Maybe your issue has already been discussed in the **freeDSP forum**. There might already be a solution for the problem you are facing. Please use the ‘Digital Line Level’ subforum @ diyAudio.com to connect with other people working with the freeDSP. Please create individual threads for your topics. Link these threads in the [**freeDSP main thread**](http://www.diyaudio.com/forums/digital-line-level/285260-freedsp-main-thread.html) \- so that others can find them.  
3. **We cannot provide support via email or the contact form on the website.** We hope that you understand that freeDSP is not a commercial product. It is an **open-source spare-time project**. We hope that questions can be answered together with the freeDSP community in the upcoming freeDSP forum. Please be patient and remember that forums work on a voluntary basis.  If you post to a **forum**, please provide:   
   1. The version of the freeDSP board you are working with. A good resolution photo of your soldered board from top and bottom. If you made some changes to the original design, please describe them in detail.  
   2. A detailed and clear explanation of the symptoms you are seeing.  
   3. A description of the troubleshooting steps you already performed and the results obtained.

# **Appendix** {#appendix}

## **Specifications** {#specifications}

| Digital Signal Processor | ADAU1701 audio DSP with 2 ADCs and 4 DACs integrated |
| :---- | :---- |
| **Sampling rate** | 44.1 kHz / 48 kHz (max. 96 kHz) |
| **Bit depth** | 24 bit (internal 28 bit single precision/56 bit double precision) |
| **Programming** | Graphic oriented programming with SigmaStudio (Windows only) and a USBi programming adapter or an Arduino |
| **Analog audio connections** | 2 channel analog input, 4 channel analog output, 4 channel amplified speaker output |
| **Input impedance** | 2 kΩ \+ external resistors (depends on chosen jumper) |
| **Output impedance AMP** | 0.19 Ω |
| **Dynamic range** | 78 dB /w digital in @4.7VRMS @1kHz |
| **Total Harmonic Distortion** | \<0.01% @4.7VRMS @1kHz |
| **Digital audio connections** | S/PDIF in (RCA or TOSLINK), S/PDIF out (RCA or Toslink) |
| **General purpose input/output interface** | On pin header |

## **Input sensitivity options** {#input-sensitivity-options}

The input sensitivity of the freeDSP ALLinONE  is configurable via jumpers. You can customize the input sensitivity in even finer steps with user-defined resistors at the input channels. Table 5 shows all implemented resistor values and the corresponding maximum RMS input voltage. Note, that the output signal is always max. 0.9 V RMS (analog out of the DSP, not the AMPs).

| External resistance | Maximum RMS input voltage |
| :---- | :---- |
| 7.15 kΩ | 0.9 V (default) |
| 10.6 kΩ | 1.26 V (+2 dBV) |
| 18 kΩ | 2.0 V (+6 dBV) |

**Table 5 \- Input sensitivity options**

ADC0/ADC1 pins use a series of voltage-to-current resistors; an internal 2kΩ and a configurable external resistor. Therefore user-defined resistor values can be calculated using following equation:

Rext=Uin,RMS100µA-2kΩ

![][image24]  
**Figure 23 \- Input sensitivity resistors**

A tolerance of 1% for these resistors is recommended  \[ADAU, p. 20\]. For further information it is recommended to refer to the [standard audio line levels](https://www.kfs.oeaw.ac.at/manual/3.8/html/userguide/461.htm).

## **Digital Signal Processor** {#digital-signal-processor}

The DSP is the CPU and therefore the most fundamental part of the device. In combination with several other FreeDSP boards we are using the ADAU1701 \[ADAU\]. In the following pages the DSP is often referred to as ADAU. The processor has analog inputs and analog outputs. You can find the analog outputs on a pin strip (P6). However these are not the main focus of this project, but might be used for debugging. More important are the MP (Multipurpose Pins) of which the DSP has 12\. MP0-3 are used for Input, MP4, 5 for Input LRCLK and BCLK, MP6-9 for output and MP10,11 for Output LRCLK and BCLK \[ADAU, p. 46\]. MP0, MP4 and MP5 are connected to S/PDIF In, the AMPs are using MP6,7 and MP10,11 and S/PDIF Out is assigned to MP9-11. The standard connector is using MP1, MP8 and MP11, 12 for clock. After these implementations we still have the input MPs (MP2,3) which are unused. Instead of leaving them unconnected we decided to make them available by putting them on the board with a pin header. You can use them however you wish to.

## **AMP** {#amp}

The target of this project is, to merge several freeDSP functionalities on one board. With the freeDSP ALLinONE  a fully function allround DSP board is provided. Thus two audio amplifiers were implemented. Each contains an amplification IC \[TAS5760M\] which is connected to one MP port of the ADAU. With them you can plug this board directly to your loudspeakers via the AMP outputs and without any other device in between. The PCB Layout has been made following the instructions given in the datasheet \[TAS5760M\]. Furthermore, each amplifier has a Schmitt-triggered Inverter which is placed next to the amplification ICs and is used to let the ICs shut down smoothly. In our current design, we decided to use several measurement points in order to check if the amplification IC is working properly. We recommend to keep them as not having them on your board will impede any error searches in case of malfunction. However you are free to remove them if you want to free up some space on the board. The first AMP has measurement points at MCLK, SCLK, SDIN and LRCK and for the second one we suggest it is sufficient to have just one measurement point at MCLK. Please note that the AMP is designed to work with supply voltage from 5 to 30V \[TAS5760M\].

## **S/PDIF** {#s/pdif}

The freeDSP ALLinONE  board supports S/PDIF audio format as input and output for digital audio data. Therefore a receiver and transmitter IC is required. As Cirrus Logic does not provide a transreceiver with an asynchronous sample rate converter and an input voltage of 3.3V, we decided to use two separate components.  
Digital audio data of any sample rate is received, converted to I2S format and resampled to match the following internal I2S specifications:

* I2S 24 bit-data  
* Left-right-clock: f=48 kHz  
* Bit-clock: f \= 32248 kHz \=3.072 MHz

More information about serial audio data can be found [here](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1S74mOQIim-wwMh_L6k44ab7wNwmPWRSnGynF-zREvO4/edit).

![][image25]

**Figure 24 \- I2S overview**

Figure 24 points out the general working principle.  
After converting the incoming signal, S/PDIF receiver \[CS8422\] propagates the I2S data (series data, left-right-clock and bit-clock) to the DSP. Both output data and clocks are sent in I2S format to S/PDIF transmitter \[CS8406\] on the other hand. Moreover, I2S is used to transmit the digital audio signals from the DSP to the AMPs.  
As the clock input pins of ADAU1701 can only work in I2S slave mode, CS8422 operates in master mode \[ADAU1701: p. 46\]. CS8406 is set to be slave concerning the I2S protocol.  
Receiver, DSP and transmitter receive the signal of the external clock oscillator in order to have synchronous internal clocks. If you decide to exclude either S/PDIF receiver or transmitter, it is recommended to omit the corresponding line termination resistor as well. For more details please check the chapter [Line termination](#heading=h.i52vdcm73mfu).

**S/PDIF In**  
The CS8422 was chosen because of its compatibility to S/PDIF signals and its internal asynchronous sample rate converter. This component is needed in order to guarantee that the converted signals match the I2S specifications mentioned above.  
Figure 25 taken out of the technical documentation \[CS8422: p. 40\] shows the clock routing in hardware mode. Firstly, the internal PLL is used to clock the sample rate converter. Secondly, the external oscillator clock is internally divided by 512 resulting in a 48 kHz LRCLK.  
Moreover, CS8422 has two differential fully separated receiver inputs. So you can choose between the TOSLINK receiver and the RCA by using a jumper.  
  ![][image26]  
**Figure 25 \- Clock Routing in CS8422**

However, CS8422 is only available with a 32 QNF package.

**S/PDIF Out**  
As the S/PDIF transmitter uses the same oscillator clock as master clock as the DSP, there is no clock skew or frequency drift between DSP and S/PDIF Codecs. Another advantage of CS8406 is its Stand-Alone Mode. Therefore it can be configured by external components in order to function without a microcontroller \[CS8406: p. 11-12\].  
The differential output drivers are used to connect TOSLINK and RCA transmitters. 

**External Components**

### **![][image27]**

**Figure 26 \- External Components for S/PDIF**

A transformer is used to achieve isolation. We chose one fabricated by Murata because it was specially designed for S/PDIF circuits. The 75Ω resistor matches the impedance to prevent reflections. Same methods are applied to the external output components.  
Instead of using a transceiver for the TOSLINK interface, we preferred to separate receiver and transmitter. So if one does not want to implement both S/PDIF components, one external component can be omitted.

## **Clock Distribution** {#clock-distribution}

**Specifications**

* Master clock frequency 24.576MHz (512x fs)  
* 6 separate output buffers in use (1x ADAU, 1x standard connector, 2x AMP, 1x S/PDIF In, 1x S/PDIF Out)  
* Frequency stability: \+/- 20ppm \[AbraconASV\]  
* Jitter (1σ): 3.2 ps \[AbravonASV\]  
* series termination

**Clock Generator**  
As a sampling frequency of 48kHz is used for the DSP and S/PDIF interface, there is a master clock frequency of 24.576MHz needed (512\*fs mode of the ADAU is chosen). There are several ways to provide a clock e.g. Pierce-oscillator, however the method implemented in this case adopts the integrated oscillator \[AbraconASV\] used in the SMD-B. For further information on this topic, please refer to \[SMD-B\].

**Clock Buffer**  
Six different units of the freeDSP ALLinONE  board have to be supplied by the master clock. Because of that, our system requires a clock buffer. We need one clock output to be connected to the ADAU, two to the AMPs, one to the standard connector, one to S/PDIF In and one to S/PDIF out. Therefore the output low-cost buffer IDT2305 used by the SMD-B version was replaced by an IDT buffer optimized for high-speed clocks being able to drive up to nine separate outputs \[IDT2309NZ\]. The maximum of the output-output skew of 250ps remains the same. Still, three outputs of the buffer are unused. Our first thought was to let these outputs floating, however in case of any possible problems that may derivate from leaving them unconnected, we decided to bring measurement points next to the corresponding pins. By that we are able to fix potential malfunctions by easily being able to manually assign any voltage to the pins or to drag those outputs to ground. Initial testing suggested that the clock distribution works properly without doing any of this, so that you may build the PCB without the measurement points next to the clock buffer. However, for debug reasons, it is recommended, to keep all measurement points.

**Line Termination**  
We implemented a termination technique to our clock buffer in order to achieve a high-quality clock signal. A mismatch between the impedances of output buffer Zout, transmission Z0L and load can cause reflections at high frequencies which have a negative impact on the signal quality of the clock. Therefore series termination was used:

![][image28]   
**Figure 27 \- Series line termination**

An external resistor Rterm ensures impedance matching \[Patoux\].

Rterm=Z0L-Zout

A simulation of the output impedance of the clock buffer using an IBIS-Model downloaded from manufacturer’s website resulted in Zout=15.3Ω. As the line resistance Z0L is about 50Ω, the value of the termination resistor was chosen to be Rterm34Ω.

The following simulations show the effect of using a termination resistor on a lossy transmission line. The use of the the termination resistor resulted in a significantly lower overshoot. A larger resistor value (100Ω) would reduce the overshoot even more but has a greater negative impact on rise and fall time.

## **Power Supply** {#power-supply}

The problem we faced supplying the power for the freeDSP ALLinONE  was that we had to provide two different voltage levels within the board. For example, the analog parts of the AMP need from 4.5V to 24V. The higher the supply voltage at the freeDSP ALLinONE  is, the more power can be consumed by the AMPs. For example you may achieve an enhanced bass playback volume with increased supply voltage. The ADAU and all the digital components of the board need 3.3V.  
After ESD-Protection and smoothing the voltage connected to P13 is directly linked to the analog parts of the AMPs. These steps are also mandatory for protecting the switching regulator. For rectifying, the \[FES10D\] diode is applied. It can operate up to 10A which makes it suitable for our application where up to 4 loudspeakers can be driven.  
Imax=Usupply,minPAMP,max=6V415W=10A  
The LM2842Y Step-Down DC-DC Regulator \[LM2842Y\] is used in order to regulate the voltage down to 3.3V and to supply all the digital parts of the PCB. We opted for this regulator as it supports a maximum typical switch current of 1.15A \[LM2842Y\], making it suitable for our application, having to provide several integrated circuits (ADAU, S/PDIF, AMPs). Besides that, switching regulators are known to be more efficient compared to linear regulators, even if they are more noisy. Not the 3.3V ripple, nor its noise should affect the main functions of the board, as it is primary provided as supply voltage for digital communication circuits. To avoid any quality decreasing effects, you may use the digital S/PDIF inputs as well. As a wide range, low power dissipation and compact outline switching regulator, the LM284x has been chosen to provide the digital voltage supply. The regulator operates at 1.25 MHz and is able to support even low impedance up to 6 Ohms without further problems.  
RL,min=USRISR,min=3.3V600mA\<6  
When doing the PCB Layout we followed the instruction given in the datasheet in order to guarantee noise reduction \[LM2842Y, p. 16\]. The different capacities, a diode and an inductance were placed as close as possible to the LM2842Y using extra planes for Vin, Vout and GND.   
To achieve a low theoretical ripple current of around 40.7 mA according to the \[LM2842Y\] datasheet and the there given formula

L=(Vin-Vout)VoutVinIripplefsw  
we decided to use a 47µH inductance.
